tion Paysanne, one of France's largest farmers' unions, has successfully fought against genetically modified organisms (GMOs), but unlike other allied movements, theirs has been led by producers rather than consumers. In Food, Farms, and Solidarity, Chaia Heller analyzes the group's complex strategies and campaigns, including a call for a Europe-wide ban on GM crops and hormone-treated beef, and a protest staged at a McDonald's. Her study of the Confédération Paysanne shows the challenges small farms face in a postindustrial agricultural world. Heller also reveals how the language the union uses to argue against GMOs encompasses more than the risks they pose; emphasizing solidarity has allowed farmers to focus on food as a cultural practice and align themselves with other workers. Heller's examination of the Confédération Paysanne's commitment to a vision of alter-globalization, the idea of substantive alternatives to neoliberal globalization, demonstrates how ecological and social justice can be restored in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAgriculture and statezFrance. 0aAnti-globalization movementzFrance. 0aFarmersxPolitical activityxHistoryy20th centuryzFrance. 0aGenetically modified foodsxPolitical aspectszFrance. 0aSustainable agriculturezFrance. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478092117?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478092117zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478092117/original  a978-3-11-0711